			<h1>Finding the Pizza of Naples in New York</h1>
			
		  <table class="author" width="100%">
			<tr>
		  <td align="left">
			<div>By John Healy</div><div>Special to The <span style="color:#09c">Epoch</span> Times</div>
			  </td>
				<td align="right">May 31,  2006</td>
				</tr></table>

			<br>


<div class="right" style="width: 320px; padding: 6px">

			<div class="articleimage " style="width: 308px">

				<a href="/news_images/highres/2006-5-30-pizza.jpg" target="_blank">
				<div class="image"><img src="/news_images/2006-5-30-pizza.jpg" style="width: 300px; height: 200px"></div>
				</a>

				<div class="caption">NAPLES TO NEW YORK: A Neapolitan pizza at Una Pizza Napoletana in Lower Manhattan. (Mary Blanco)
</div>

		</div>


</div>


	
	<div class="content">

	<p>NEW YORK — There are over 60,000 pizzerias in the United States, but those that dish out a true Neapolitan pizza are a small fraction. In New York City, there are only a few pizzerias that claim to make an authentic Neapolitan pizza. I desired to explore two of them in different Manhattan neighborhoods.

<p> In Naples, Italy, pizza is intended to be flatbread about 10 inches in diameter (about 4 slices), a quarter inch thick (with a puffy rim) and baked in a wood-burning oven. Originally, the pizza was topped with lard, but at the end on the 18th century, Neapolitans began topping it with their newfound love—tomato.

<p> Eventually, in 1889, to honor the visit of Queen Margherita of Italy to Naples, at Brandi, one of the most ancient pizzerias in the city, mozzarella and basil were added to tomato to recreate the colors of the Italian flag—thus, the Margherita pizza was created.

<p> <h3> Una Pizza Napoletana</h3> 

<p> Anthony Mangieri is obsessed with true Neapolitan pizza, as the name of his modest-looking pizzeria suggests. He takes enormous pride in his wood-burning oven built for him just like those in Naples. He pays a lot of attention to ingredients. Indeed, he tops his dough—made entirely with soft flour and fresh yeast—for Margherita pizza, only with San Marzano tomatoes, extra virgin olive oil and fresh mozzarella cheese. The result is very close to the better pizzas that I enjoyed while in Naples. The center of the pie is wetter than the centers of American-style pizzas and it can be folded upon itself twice, just as tradition demands in Naples. In fact, Neapolitans disdain crispy thin-crust pizzas, and prefer a softer, chewier version.

<p> Mr. Mangieri also offers a first-rate cheeseless Marinara pizza, a tomatoless pizza "bianca" and an outstanding "filetto" pizza with fresh rather than canned tomatoes.

<p> He is also a very original character. He only opens Una Pizza Napoletana Thursday through Sunday, and as a sign in his window states, the closing time is determined by the amount of pizza he has sold throughout the day. 

<p> His pizzas are also rather expensive at $17 each, given the modest premise and service, but definitely worth trying.

<p> Una Pizza Napoletana<br> <GEO TYPE="US">349 12th Street New York, NY</GEO> (212) 477-9950. Cash Only.

<p> <h3> Celeste</h3> 

<p> Giancarlo Quadalti, the chef and owner of Celeste, a charming small pizzeria on the Upper West Side, shares the same passion for Neapolitan pizza as Mr. Mangieri. However, in an effort to cater to American taste, he drains the San Marzano tomatoes before adding them to the pie in order to attain a crispier and drier center. In addition, he is far less traditional in his approach to pizza, and serves original pizzas, such as an addictively good one topped with soft stracchino cheese, air-cured bresaola and fresh arugola. They all cost around $10 each and can make a wonderful start to the meal.

<p> At Celeste, you can also taste some terrific Neapolitan dishes. The fried buffalo ricotta cheese is divinely silky, and the gnocchi with fresh tomato sauce ethereally light. The dining room director is a great cheese aficionado, and it is worth skipping dessert in favor of one of his assorted cheese plates accompanied by different fruit preserves and honeys.

<p> The wine list is quite extensive and full of Italian choices under $30 and can complement your dinner quite nicely.

<p> Celeste<br> <GEO TYPE="US">502 Amsterdam Ave. New York, NY</GEO> (212) 874-4559. Cash Only.

<p> Email John Healy at restaurant@epochtimes.com
	</div>




